# Mock API Rules

All data fetching is abstracted through `lib/api/` even while using mocks.
When the real API is ready, only the files inside `lib/api/mock/` need to change.
All API types are defined in `lib/api/types.ts`.
Always import from there — never redefine types inline in components.

## Required folder structure

lib/
api/
mock/
movies.ts ← mock data arrays, typed to match DB schema
showtimes.ts
theaters.ts
bookings.ts
users.ts
movies.ts ← exported async functions, currently calls mock data
showtimes.ts
theaters.ts
bookings.ts
users.ts
types.ts ← all API response types matching the DB schema exactly

## Mock data field names must match the DB schema

Use these exact field names (from the agreed schema):

- Movies: id, movie_name, director, movie_poster_url, genre, description, created_by, created_at
- Showtimes: id, movie_id, theater_id, show_datetime, status, created_at
- Theaters: id, name, total_rows, total_columns
- TheaterSeats: id, theater_id, row_label, column_number, seat_name, seat_type, base_price, is_active
- Bookings: id, user_id, showtime_id, booking_ref, total_amount, status, booked_at
- BookingSeats: id, booking_id, seat_id, price_at_booking

## API function pattern — every function must follow this signature

// List with pagination
getMovies(params?: MovieQueryParams): Promise<PaginatedResponse<Movie>>

// Single item
getMovieById(id: number): Promise<Movie>

// Related resources
getShowtimesByMovie(movieId: number): Promise<Showtime[]>
getSeatsByShowtime(showtimeId: number): Promise<SeatAvailability[]>

// Mutations
createBooking(payload: CreateBookingPayload): Promise<Booking>
cancelBooking(bookingId: number): Promise<Booking>

## Simulating async behavior in mocks

Every mock function must use an artificial delay:
await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 300));
This ensures components handle loading states correctly before the real API lands.

## PaginatedResponse shape

interface PaginatedResponse<T> {
data: T[];
total: number;
page: number;
per_page: number;
}
